heading_context: Get an advance on your first benefit payment
chunks.html_content:
You may be able to get an advance on your first benefit payment if you’re in urgent financial need.

You usually pay it back through your benefits. You do not have to pay interest.
chunks.plain_content:

heading_context: Get an advance on your first benefit payment
chunks.html_content:
You can ask for an advance if you’ve recently applied for:

  • Universal Credit
  • Jobseeker’s Allowance (JSA)
  • Employment and Support Allowance (ESA)
  • Carer’s Allowance
  • Pension Credit
  • State Pension

You’ll be told when you’ll be paid and how much. You’ll usually be paid on the same day or the next working day. It’ll be paid into your bank or Post Office account.

heading_context: Get an advance on your first benefit payment
If you cannot use the phone
chunks.html_content:
Find out about call charges.

You can ask to use the phone in your local Jobcentre Plus if you cannot afford to make a phone call.

Ask a Jobcentre Plus adviser to assess you and apply on your behalf if you’re unable to speak on the phone.

heading_context: Get an advance on your first benefit payment
chunks.html_content: You might be able to ask for another advance straight after getting one or being turned down. You can only do this if you can show that your circumstances have changed, meaning you need more money than you previously thought.
chunks.plain_content:
Get an advance on your first benefit payment
Getting another advance
You might be able to ask for another advance straight after getting one or being turned down. You can only do this if you can show that your circumstances have changed, meaning you need more money than you previously thought.

heading_context: Get an advance on your first benefit payment
chunks.html_content: The adviser will tell you how to pay back the advance. Usually a little will be taken from each of your benefit payments until it’s paid back. You do not have to pay interest on it.
chunks.plain_content:
Get an advance on your first benefit payment
Paying it back
The adviser will tell you how to pay back the advance. Usually a little will be taken from each of your benefit payments until it’s paid back. You do not have to pay interest on it.

heading_context: Get an advance on your first benefit payment
If you’re not happy with a decision
chunks.html_content: You can ask for a decision to be reconsidered if you’re not happy with it. Say this when you’re told the decision.
chunks.plain_content:

If you’re not happy with a decision
You can ask for a decision to be reconsidered if you’re not happy with it. Say this when you’re told the decision.
